{{Infobox language family |name=Dagan |altname=Meneao Range |region=Southeastern peninsula of {{nowrap|[[New Guinea]]}} |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] |fam2=[[Papuan Peninsula languages|Papuan Peninsula]] |glotto=daga1274 |glottorefname=Dagan }}
The '''Dagan languages''' are a small family of [[Trans&ndash;New Guinea]] (TNG) languages spoken in the "[[Bird's Tail]]" (southeastern peninsula) of New Guinea, the easternmost Papuan languages on the mainland. They are sometimes included in a speculative [[Southeast Papuan languages|Southeast Papuan]] branch of Trans&ndash;New Guinea (TNG), but the Southeast Papuan families have not been shown to be any more closely related to each other than they are to other TNG families.
The languages are: :[[Daga language|Daga]], [[Mapena language|Mapena]], [[Maiwa language|Maiwa]], [[Dima language|Dima]] (Jimajima), [[Ginuman language|Ginuman]], [[Kanasi language|Kanasi]] (Sona), [[Onjob language|Onjob]], [[Umanakaina language|Umanakaina]] (Gwedena), and the nearly extinct [[Turaka language|Turaka]].
Although clearly related, they are not particularly close. The closest language to Umanakaina, for example, is Ginuman, which is only 23% lexically similar. Pronouns are:
:{| ! !!sg!!pl |- !1 |*na||*nu |- !2 |*ga||*ya |- !3 |*me, *-e||*m[a]u |}
