'''Traditional Day''' or '''Fête du Vodoun''' (literally Vodoun Festival, also known as Traditional Religions Day) is a [[public holiday]] in [[Benin]] that celebrates the nation's history surrounding the West African religion of [[Vodoun]]. The celebration is held annually on January 10 throughout the country but most notably in the city of [[Ouidah]]. Beginning with the [[Ritual slaughter|slaughter of a goat]] in honor of the spirits, the festival is filled with singing, dancing and the imbibing of liquor, especially [[gin]]. Vodoun was officially declared a religion in Benin in 1996 and the festival has attracted thousands of devotees and tourists to Ouidah to participate in the festivities ever since.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/1756057.stm |title=Benin marks Voodoo Day |date=2002-11-11 | work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://journals.worldnomads.com/worldfestivals/story/32700/Benin/January-Voodoo-Festival-Benin |title=January - Voodoo Festival, Benin |date=2008-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transafrica.biz/festivals/festivals-events-in-benin/ |title=Voodoo, a traditional religion on the Gulf of Guinea Coast }}</ref>

