{{For|the group of modern-day Romance varieties of Switzerland and Italy|Lombard language}} {{Infobox language |name=Lombardic |altname= ''Langobardic'' |region=[[Pannonia]] and [[Italy]] |era=[[Middle Ages]] |extinct=11th century |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Germanic languages|Germanic]] |fam3=[[West Germanic languages|West Germanic]] |fam4=[[High German languages|Upper German]] |script=[[Elder Futhark inscriptions#Continental|Runic script]], later shifted to [[Latin script]] |iso3=lng |linglist=lng |glotto=none |notice=IPA }}
'''Lombardic''' or '''Langobardic''' is an extinct [[West Germanic language]] that was spoken by the [[Lombards]] (''Langobardi''), the [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] people who settled in [[Italy]] in the 6th century. It was already rapidly declining by the seventh century because the invaders quickly adopted the [[Vulgar Latin|Latin vernacular]] spoken by the local Gallo-Roman population. Lombardic may have been in scattered use until as late as c. AD 1000. A number of Italian place names and items of [[Italian language|Italian]] vocabulary derive from Lombardic. Some linguists have argued that the modern [[Cimbrian language|Cimbrian]] and [[Mòcheno language|Mocheno]] varieties in [[Northeast Italy]], usually classified as Austro-Bavarian, are in fact surviving Lombard remnants.<ref>Bruno Schweizer: ''Die Herkunft der Zimbern''. In: ''Die Nachbarn. Jahrbuch für vergleichende Volkskunde 1'', 1948, ISSN 0547-096X, S. 111–129.; Alfonso Bellotto: ''Il cimbro e la tradizione longobarda nel vicentino I.'' In: ''Vita di Giazza e di Roana 17-18'', (1974) S. 7–19; ''Il cimbro e la tradizione longobarda nel vicentino II.'' In: ''Vita di Giazza e di Roana 19-20'', (1974) S. 49–59.</ref><ref>Ermenegildo Bidese ''Die Zimbern und ihre Sprache: Geographische, historische und sprachwissenschaftlich relevante Aspekte''. In: Thomas Stolz (ed.): ''Kolloquium über Alte Sprachen und Sprachstufen. Beiträge zum Bremer Kolloquium über „Alte Sprachen und Sprachstufen“. (= Diversitas Linguarum, Volume 8)''. Verlag Brockmeyer, Bochum 2004, {{ISBN|3-8196-0664-5}}, S. 3–42.[http://portale.unitn.it/ateneo/persone/ermenegildo.bidese Webseite von Ermenegildo Bidese]</ref> This could, in turn, indicate that Lombardic was itself an Austro-Bavarian dialect.
==Overview== Lombardic is preserved only fragmentarily, the main evidence being individual words used in [[Latin]] texts. For example, the [[Edict of Rothari]] of 643, the earliest Lombard legal code, is written in Latin, with only individual legal terms given in Lombardic. The many Lombard personal names preserved in Latin deeds from the [[Kingdom of the Lombards]] also provide evidence of the language.
In the absence of Lombardic texts, it is not possible to draw any conclusions about its morphology and syntax. The genetic classification is necessarily based entirely on phonology. Because there is evidence that Lombardic participated in, and indeed shows some of the earliest evidence for, the [[High German consonant shift]], it is classified as an [[Elbe Germanic]] or [[Upper German]] dialect. The [[Historia Langobardorum]] of [[Paulus Diaconus]] mentions a duke [[Zaban]] of 574, showing {{IPA|/t/}} shifted to {{IPA|/ts/}}. The term ''stolesazo'' (ablative)<ref>''Edictus rothari'', cap. 150: "[...] districtus ab stolesazo."</ref> (the second element is cognate with English ''seat'') in the [[Edictum Rothari]] shows the same shift. Many names in the Lombard royal families show shifted consonants, particularly {{IPA|/p/}} < {{IPA|/b/}} in the following name components: * ''pert'' < ''bert'': Aripert, Godepert * ''perg'' < ''berg'': Gundperga (daughter of [[Agilulf|King Agilulf]]) * ''prand'' < ''brand'': Ansprand, Liutprand
This [[sound change]] left two different sets of names in the [[Italian language]]: palco (longobard palk, "beam")/balcone (longobard balk, "wood platform"); panca (longobard panka)/banca (longobard banka, "bench").<ref>Giacomo Devoto, ''Dizionario etimologico''.</ref>
Formerly, Lombardic was classified as [[Ingaevonian]] (North Sea Germanic) or as [[Eastern Germanic]], but these classifications are considered obsolete.<ref>{{LexMA|5|1698|1699|Langobardisch|Federico Albano Leoni}}</ref> The classification of Lombardic within the Germanic languages may be complicated by issues of orthography. According to Hutterer (1999) it is close to [[Old Saxon]]. [[Tacitus]] counts them among the [[Suebi]]. [[Paulus Diaconus]] (8th century) and the ''Codex Gothanus'' (9th century) wrote that the Lombards were ultimately of Scandinavian origin, having settled at the [[Elbe]] before entering Italy.
Lombardic fragments are preserved in [[rune|runic]] inscriptions, in Latinized forms, and in transcriptions influenced by [[Old High German]] orthography. This ''Lombardic alphabet'', as commonly transcribed, consists of the following graphemes:{{sfn|Hutterer|1999|page=339}}
{{block indent|''a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, i, j, k, l, m, n, o, p, q(u), r, s, {{IPA|ʒ}}, t, [[þ]], u, w, z''}}
The ''qu'' represents a {{IPA|[kw]}} sound. The ''ʒ'' is {{IPA|[s]}}, e.g. ''skauʒ'' {{IPA|[skaus]}} "womb"<!-- glossed in German, "Schoß" -->. The ''z'' is {{IPA|[ts]}}. ''h'' is {{IPA|[h]}} word-initially, and {{IPA|[x]}} elsewhere.
Among the primary source texts are short inscriptions in the [[Elder Futhark]], among them the "bronze capsule of [[Schretzheim]]" (c. 600): *On the lid: '''arogisd''' *On the bottom: '''alaguþleuba : dedun''' *("Arogisl/-gast. Alaguth (and) Leuba made (it)",<ref>J.H. Looijenga, ''Runes Around The North Sea And On The Continent Ad 150-700'', PhD diss. Groningen 1997, p. 158. [https://web.archive.org/web/20050502101056/http://dissertations.ub.rug.nl/FILES/faculties/arts/1997/j.h.looijenga/thesis.pdf Download PDF]</ref> less likely "Arogis and Alaguth made love")
And also the two fibulae of [[Bezenye]], [[Hungary]] (mid 6th century): *Fibula A: '''godahid unj[a]''' *Fibula B: '''(k?)arsiboda segun''' *("To Godahi(l)d, (with) sympathy (?), Arsiboda's bless"<ref>J.H. Looijenga, ''Runes Around The North Sea And On The Continent Ad 150-700'', PhD diss. Groningen 1997, p. 134. [http://dissertations.ub.rug.nl/FILES/faculties/arts/1997/j.h.looijenga/thesis.pdf Download PDF] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716114809/http://dissertations.ub.rug.nl/FILES/faculties/arts/1997/j.h.looijenga/thesis.pdf |date=2011-07-16 }}</ref>)
There are a number of Latin texts that include Lombardic names, and Lombardic legal texts contain terms taken from the legal vocabulary of the vernacular, including: *[[Origo gentis Langobardorum]] *[[Paulus Diaconus]], [[Historia Langobardorum]] *[[Historia Langobardorum codicis Gothani]] *[[Edictum Rothari]]
In 2006, Emilia Denčeva argued that the inscription of the [[Pernik sword]] may be Lombardic.{{sfn|Dentschewa|2006}}
