{{infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = The Sword and the Sickle | title_orig = | translator = | image = <!--prefer 1st edition--> | caption = | author = [[Mulk Raj Anand]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[India]] | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | genre = [[Novel]] | publisher = | release_date = 1942 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print | pages = | isbn = | oclc = 3850942 | congress = PR9499.3.A5 | preceded_by = [[Across the Black Waters]] | followed_by = [[The Private Life of an Indian Prince]] }} '''''The Sword and the Sickle''''' is a [[novel]] by [[Mulk Raj Anand]] first published in 1942. Like his other novels, this one also deals with the topic of social and political structures, specifically, the rise of [[Communism]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/lr/2005/12/04/stories/2005120400090200.htm|title=Poetics of Protest|date=December 4, 2005|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref> The title for the book was given to Anand by [[George Orwell]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1472853/Mulk-Raj-Anand.html|title=Mulk Raj Anand|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=2009-08-31 | location=London | date=2004-09-29}}</ref> The novel was in keeping with [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[United States|American]] writings of the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/the-end-of-an-era/67601/0|title=The end of an era|date=October 3, 2004|publisher=[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref> The book was the final part of the trilogy that included ''[[The Village (Anand novel)|The Village]]'' and ''[[Across the Black Waters]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=George|first=C. J,|title=Mulk Raj Anand, his art and concerns: a study of his non-autobiographical novels|publisher=Atlantic Publishers|year=1994|pages=77|isbn=978-81-7156-445-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M7LSHdlvRtcC&lpg=PA51&dq=%22Two%20Leaves%20and%20a%20Bud%22%2B%22Mulk%20Raj%20Anand%22&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q=%22Two%20Leaves%20and%20a%20Bud%22+%22Mulk%20Raj%20Anand%22&f=false|accessdate=2009-08-31}}</ref>
