{{infobox ancient site | name = Zhiren Cave | native_name = 智人洞 | native_name_lang = zh | alternate_name = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | map = | map_type = China | map_alt = Zhiren Cave | map_caption =location in China | map_size = 240 | relief = yes | coordinates = {{coord|22|17|13.6|N|107|30|45.1|E|display=inline,title}} | map_dot_label = | location = [[Guangxi]], China | region = | type = | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | volume = | diameter = | circumference = | height = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = early [[Late Pleistocene]] | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | other_designation = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }} '''Zhiren Cave''' ({{zh|c=智人洞}}) is a [[karstic]] cave in the Mulan Mountains that overlooks the Hejiang River in [[Chongzuo]], [[Guangxi]], China.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} Zhiren Cave is an early [[Late Pleistocene]] site that has yielded the fossil remains of possibly [[anatomically modern humans]] with some mixed [[archaic human]] features.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}}{{sfn|Kaufman|2010}}
==Fossils== The fossil remains were discovered by Chinese paleontologists in 2007.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} The fossils were covered by a continuous layer of [[flowstone]], a layer that was initially dated to around 113,000 to 100,000 [[Before Present|BP]].{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} A more thorough re-dating was later undertaken, and gives an estimated date of around 116,000 to 106,000 BP.{{sfn|Cai|Qiang|Wang|Jin|2017}}
Some of the large mammal remains discovered at Zhiren Cave include those from ''[[Pongo pygmaeus]]'', ''Elephas kiangnanensis'', ''[[Elephas maximus]]'', ''[[Megatapirus augustus]]'', ''Rhinoceros sinensis'', ''Megalovis guangxiensis'', [[Cervus unicolor]], ''[[Ursus thibetanus]]'', ''[[Arctonyx collaris]]'' and ''[[Panthera pardus]]''.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} Around 25% of the large mammal species discovered at the site are now extinct.{{sfn|Dennell|2010}}
Three pieces of hominin remains were identified: two upper molars (''Zhiren 1'' and ''Zhiren 2'') and an anterior [[mandible]] (''Zhiren 3'').{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} The fossils are believed to have belonged to at least two different individuals, as ''Zhiren 1'' and ''Zhiren 3'' are unlikely to have come from the same individual.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}}
When compared to Late Pleistocene fossils from western Eurasia, ''Zhiren 1'' and ''Zhiren 2'' are smaller and would be classified as modern; however, the comparative context is lacking in East Asian Late Pleistocene fossils.{{sfn|Dennell|2010}}{{sfn|Dennell|2014|pp=45-46}} Zhiren 2 shows evidence for dental winging in its lower incisors, a feature that has only been found in ''Homo sapiens''.{{sfn|Martinón-Torres|Wu|Bermúdez de Castro|Xing|2017}}
''Zhiren 3'' contains a mix of archaic and modern human features.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} The most significant aspect of ''Zhiren 3'' is that it has a distinctively modern human chin.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} Coupled with the dating, ''Zhiren 3'' could possibly represent the earliest modern human fossil in East Asian.{{sfn|Liu|Jin|Zhang|Cai|2010}} However, many were skeptical of this conclusion, since this would significantly push back the general consensus on the dating of [[Recent African origin of modern humans|human migration out of Africa]].{{sfn|Dennell|2010}}{{sfn|Dennell|2014|pp=45-46}} [[Peter Bellwood]] also cites the lack of archaeological finds associated with the fossils.{{sfn|Bellwood|2013}}
